&lt;p&gt;This is what the rendered webpage looks like in IE9&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="./image.axd?picture=image_116.png"&gt;&lt;img style="background-image: none; border-bottom: 0px; border-left: 0px; margin: 0px; padding-left: 0px; padding-right: 0px; display: inline; border-top: 0px; border-right: 0px; padding-top: 0px" title="image" border="0" alt="image" src="./image.axd?picture=image_thumb_116.png" width="244" height="141" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I was expecting the green section to be full height, I mean this always worked fine before.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;So what has happened&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;html5 &lt;span class="kwrd"&gt;&amp;lt;!&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="html"&gt;DOCTYPE&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="attr"&gt;html&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="kwrd"&gt;&amp;gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;requires a height on the html element too…and for whatever reason I never noticed this before.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3&gt;Solution:&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Add html to the first style&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="./image.axd?picture=image_117.png"&gt;&lt;img style="background-image: none; border-bottom: 0px; border-left: 0px; margin: 0px; padding-left: 0px; padding-right: 0px; display: inline; border-top: 0px; border-right: 0px; padding-top: 0px" title="image" border="0" alt="image" src="./image.axd?picture=image_thumb_117.png" width="244" height="60" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

